#get the age of houses at time of survey in months

#this would be a kind of average room size/ average size of floors

#you can also multiply values

#perks can be thought of as the amount of amenities or how accessible the home is to surrounding activites.
df['perks'] = df['view'] + df['waterfront']

Price vs. sqft_living¶

Seeing as show sqft living is the greatest indicator of price already present in the data it might be a flop not to mention it, but everyone will do that so it would be more intersting to show how taking the most promising columns like sqft_living and grade can be used together to find stronger trends i.e.. grade sqft_living. By multiplying these values you extremify the 'niceness' of a home and so find the highest prices. You can see this in the correlation matrix above! sft_living is 0.70 and grade is 0.66, but gradesqft_living is 0.75. The mission principle component analysis is to find the combination of variables that will show the strongest correlation.

In [8]:
xax = 'sqft_living'
yax = 'price'
lm = LinearRegression() 
X = df[xax].values.reshape(-1, 1)
y = df[yax].values
reg = lm.fit(X, y )

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,7))
ax = sns.scatterplot(x=xax, y=yax, data=df, hue = 'bathrooms', sizes = 1)
plt.plot(X , reg.coef_ * X + reg.intercept_)
plt.show()

If you run the cell above the variable regcoef will be the slope of the line and reg.intercept_ will be the y intercept of the line. If you run a cell , E.g.

lm = LinearRegression() X = df[xax].values.reshape(-1, 1) y = df[yax].values reg = lm.fit(X, y )

with different xax and yax, those same variable names will have different values. So when going back and forth between cells if you get unexpected result see if you are using the proper slope and intercept values.

The line of regression is a linear model for your data or you might say it shows the trend of the data. The purpose of a line of regression is to predict values you don't know given particular data, it is accomplished by minimizing the distance between the line and every datapoint.

The model is a line y = m x + b

y -> variable you want to predict x -> data you want to use to predict y

The process of minimizing the distance between points and this line determines the parameters of the model, which are the slope and intercept, m and b respectively. Using sklearn we can pull out these parameters as

m = reg.coef , b = reg.intercept

this explains why this plot is the line of regression,

plt.plot(X , reg.coef * X + reg.intercept)

same as, plt.plot(x , y = m*x + b).

As an example of how it's used, we don't have information for 11,000 sqft_living, but we want to tell someone how much the price should be given the data we do have. You can answer this question, by plugging 11,000 in for X. As below. So you would tell someone that given the data, the price of an 11,000 sqft home would be about $3,043,278. Clearly, the more linear the data is the better linear regression will be at predicting the correct values. There are other non-linear forms of regression and interpolation techinques designed to work with non-linear data.

grade vs price¶

Of course the plot's will look very similar but you can show there is a difference using the correlation matrix and the R^2 value. What this graph implies is that homes with high grade and large sqft are priced higher then those with not only low grade , low sqft, but also the middle ground homes like the ones with large sqft but low grade or vice versa.

Another way to put it, is that we're taking the data from the plot above and pushing it right by a factor of it's grade. So large houses with high grades will be 'pushed' farther right than large homes with low grades. That's why the plot looks similar because it's the same data multiplied by a factor between 1 and 13, this product though ends up creating a data spread that is more linear and can thus be modeled more effectively using linear regression.

Perks¶

I would suppose that if a house has more views and is waterfront property than it should be more expensive than those with fewer. The perks column attempts to analyze this info. The number of views range from 0 to 4 and I assume waterfront is either 0 for false or 1 for true. When we plot the price per perk we see the positive correlation. However, I am surprised still to see so many homes with a lot of perks with low prices.

At this point we can use our line of regression along with the categorization of the homes into number of perks to analyze samples of the entire dataset to see what makes these homes price differently. This process could be carried out similarly with any other variable E.g. why are homes of the same size priced differently, I suspect your conclusion would be similar to this example of perks.

In [18]:

plt.plot(X , reg.coef_ * X + reg.intercept_)
plt.show()

To explain this plot further. We see 6 groups of data ranging from those with 0 perks i.e. no views and not waterfront, to 4 perks, homes that have max views but not waterfront and lastly waterfront homes with max views. The trend line shows that as the number of perks goes up so to does price. Now we can ask questions like why are some homes priced below the trend line. We may hypothesize that houses with a particular number of perks with a price below the line of regression may be more likely to be of low grade.

Furthermore is this statement true in general, for all home or does this assertion only hold true for a particular group of homes.

In [19]:
perks = 3

#lets look at relevant data
#you can always do df[condition] to look at data where condition is true
data = df[df.perks == perks]
data_below = df[(df.perks == perks) & (df.price <  (reg.coef_* perks + reg.intercept_)[0])]
data_above = df[(df.perks == perks) & (df.price >= (reg.coef_* perks + reg.intercept_)[0])]

You can think of this in a simpler notation df[(condition1) & (condition2)] So what this is going to do is pull out data where both condition1 and condition2 are met.

condition1 condition2 result

T          T              T      ---->  get this data

F          T              F      |

T          F              F      |---> don't get this data

F          F              F      |

df[df.perks == perks] gives you every row and column of data where the value is equal to perks, which is what we assign at the top. That's why I called this dataframe data, because it contains all of the info.

df[(df.perks == perks) & (df.price < (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0])] pulls data from the original dataframe named df where perks = perks and price is below the line of regresion we know that it's data below the line of regression because that is what the value (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0]) is.

Just to explain futher the following data frames are equivalent.

data = df[(df.perks == perks) & (df.price < (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0])]

and

data = df[df.perks == perks] data = data[data.price < (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0]]

Because data is already the data where perks are say 5 so from that dataframe all you need to specify is the price you are interested in. I just wrote it the way I did, because I was thinking of the original df at the time, but everywhere you see df[(df.perks == perks) & (df.price < (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0])] you could replace it with data[df.price < (reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept)[0]] and it would do the same thing. In fact I did this later on in creating the dataframe before the bar charts.

You can flip through different plots just by changing perks to 0,1,2,3,4 or 5. The cell below the ttest function just goes through each perk value automatically showing you the sample size for each and it's corresponding statistic.

This cell also prints out the avg of the data below and above. Showing you the means of each group.

There is a lot of information in this plot. The title shows you what value of perks you are looking at. So for 5 perks we are looking at the data along the vertical line x = 5 of the plot before. The vertical line is placed at reg.coef* perks + reg.intercept or in other words the value at which that blue regression line intercects the column of red data at x = 5 from the plot before. So then all the data points to the right correspond to prices above that line and data to the left is below the line of regression. The y-axis is the grade given to these homes with perks = 5 and price of these homes are given by the x-axis. Now what we expect if our hypothesis is true is that there should be a positive trend. Which we know is generally true from looking at the entire data set, because we have already seen from running

df.corr()['price'].sort_values(ascending = False)

and observing that there is a positive correlation of 0.66 for grade. However, now that we are looking at samples in the data we are going to pick out stronger and weaker correlations than the 0.66 we saw before because the homes are different!

This shows that trends seen in samples of various sizes can also show up in larger sample sizes. But don't be surprised if you see samples of data within a dataset not behave as the bulk of the data does. Because nothing is stopping us from hand picking houses that show will show a negative correlation.

A ttest is designed to tell you if results from a study are generalizable. For example if I take a sample of data from 30 people with two groups A and B. If the mean of group A is different from group B, can I conclude that from a sample of 3 thousand people the same will be true, that the mean of the respective groups will have the same proportion?

To answer this question we need to know how similar groups A and B are, that is what the t score tells you. The higher the t score value the greater the difference is between the groups, which means the conclusion is more generalizable.

In our case+ we are selecting a sample of the data based on the number of perks. Then we are dividing this sample in to two groups by price relative to the predicted price of our linear regression model. We are then comparing the means of these two groups using the ttest. We can then compare the means of each sample based on the perk value. What we will see is that the ttest becomes more conclusive the larger the sample size becomes.

The p value is the probability that the mean was found by chance. In our case the p value is zero for each perk value. This means that it's safe to bet that if the price value is below the trend line for price vs perks than it has a low grade. Or in plain english.

If you are comparing two homes that have the same amenities/access/perks and one is more expensive than the other than the one that is more expensive is of higher grade.

In this example our,

Null Hypothesis: No statistical difference between the grade of homes priced above the trend line than those below the trend line.

But, our p-value is less than 0.05 which is by most standards, the critical p value yours must be lower than in order to reject the null hypothesis. So we reject the null hypothesis, if you reject the null hypothesis the alternate hypothesis is accepted.

Alternate Hypothesis: There is a difference in grade value between homes above and below the trend line. In a more precise language, there is a difference in the distribution of grades relative to price, among the two groups. The groups being chosen to be above or below our model prediction.

What varies is how significant the difference becomes with varying number of perks. As you can see below the sample size changes along with the ttest score.

What this prints out, are exactly the results of an independent ttest as described above for each perk value. I made the for loop just to print out all of the results.

In [27]:
xax = 'perks'
yax = 'price'

lm = LinearRegression() 
X = df[xax].values.reshape(-1, 1)
y = df[yax].values
reg = lm.fit(X, y )

perks = 5
data = df[df.perks == perks]
data_below = data[data.price <  (reg.coef_* perks + reg.intercept_)[0]]
data_above = data[data.price >= (reg.coef_* perks + reg.intercept_)[0]]

#s1 and s2 is just the data above and below grouped by grade and counted!
s1 = pd.Series(data = data_above.groupby('grade')['price'].count(), name = 'Price Above')
s2 = pd.Series(data = data_below.groupby('grade')['price'].count(), name = 'Price Below')

#this puts together a dataframe called bar_data
bar_data = pd.concat([s1 , s2], axis = 1)

So this plot shows you the distribution of homes of a given grade with the number of perks specified above. For example, if you enter perks = 5, you'll see that just about the same number of homes are in both groups, but the median for each group is not the same. For perks = 2, it is clear that there are more homes priced below our models prediction, but the mean is still less than houses priced higher.

plt.plot(X , reg.coef_ * X + reg.intercept_)
plt.show()

In conclusion:

If you wish to model the behavior of this data using linear regression, then you should find combinations of variables that increases the correlation with the target variable that you wish to predict.

Example: sqft_living * grade produces a data spread that better predicts the price of homes. This also follows from the fact that you are using more data in your prediction. If you don't know the grade of the home then this model wouldn't help you.

Using variables in the dataset we can isolate particular types of homes to analyze more closely, to see if statements that are true about particular groups are also true for the entire dataset.

Example: Groups of homes are classified by their number of perks and how much they are priced relative to the trend of the entire dataset. We find that indeed there is a statistical difference in the distribution of price among the groups

Analyzing the relationship among variables can give insight into the very meaning of the data itself.

Example: By plotting the price versus the condition we see that it has the shape of a normal distribution. (There are most likely methods to find a distribution function that best models the data.) This by itself isn't too odd, but when condition versus age is shown our linear regression shows that there is a positive trend between age and condition.
